**Abstract:**
A major essay titled "On Biblical Narratives and Their Indispensability," dated January 13, 1995. The document critiques the post-critical "Lockean" theory of linguistic communication that reduced biblical narratives to statements about facts or ideas to be assented to, arguing this fundamentally misunderstands how narratives work. It develops an alternative view where narratives refer hearers to an inhabitable dramatic world and must be heard applicatively. The essay analyzes how pre-critical Christian reading understood the Bible as God's living voice speaking to participants in ongoing sacred history, not as a text of theoretical statements.

**AI Recommendation:** Major theoretical essay on biblical hermeneutics; essential for understanding author's critique of post-Enlightenment biblical interpretation.

